R Markdown

This is an R Markdown document. Markdown is a simple formatting syntax for authoring HTML, PDF, and MS Word documents. For more details on using R Markdown see http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com.

When you click the Knit button a document will be generated that includes both content as well as the output of any embedded R code chunks within the document. You can embed an R code chunk like this:

Get the pdf

got_path <- here("data","got.pdf")
got_text <- pdf_text(got_path)

Wrangling

got_df <- data.frame(got_text) %>% 
  mutate(text_full = str_split(got_text, pattern = '\n')) %>% 
  unnest(text_full) %>% 
  mutate(text_full = str_trim(text_full))

Get the tokens (individual words) in tidy format

got_tokens <- got_df %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, text_full)
got_tokens

Remove stop words

got_stop <- got_tokens %>% 
  anti_join(stop_words) %>% 
  select(-got_text)

Check the counts again

got_swc <- got_stop %>% 
  count(word) %>% 
  arrange(-n)

Skip numbers

got_no_numeric <- got_stop %>% 
  filter(is.na(as.numeric(word)))

A word cloud of got words (non-numeric)

length(unique(got_no_numeric$word))
## [1] 11209
# The 100 most frequent
got_top100 <- got_no_numeric %>% 
  count(word) %>% 
  arrange(-n) %>% 
  head(100)
got_cloud <- ggplot(data = got_top100, aes(label = word)) +
  geom_text_wordcloud() +
  theme_minimal()

got_cloud

Customizing

ggplot(data = got_top100, aes(label = word, size = n)) +
  geom_text_wordcloud_area(aes(color = n), shape = "diamond") +
  scale_size_area(max_size = 12) +
  scale_color_gradientn(colors = c("darkgreen","blue","red")) +
  theme_minimal()

These are the most common meaningful words in got!

got_afinn <- got_stop %>%

got_afinn2_n <- got_afinn2 %>% 
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(word = fct_reorder(factor(word), n))

ggplot(data = got_afinn2_n, aes(x = word, y = n)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip()

Summarize sentiment for the report

got_summary <- got_afinn %>% 
  summarize(
    mean_score = mean(value),
    median_score = median(value)
  )

Count by sentiment and word, then facet

got_nrc_n5 <- got_nrc %>% 
  count(word,sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  group_by(sentiment) %>% 
  top_n(5) %>% 
  ungroup()

got_nrc_gg <- ggplot(data = got_nrc_n5, aes(x = reorder(word,n), y = n, fill = sentiment)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~sentiment, ncol = 2, scales = "free") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "Word", y = "count")

got_nrc_gg

ggsave(plot = got_nrc_gg, 
       here("figures","got_nrc_sentiment.png"), 
       height = 8, 
       width = 5)
